oads in 20 seconds and 15 ResourceMonitor snapshots in 200ms (should be ~1 per 10 minutes), indicating the\n    feedback loop was accelerating.\n\n   Scale of Impact (Platform-Wide)\n\n   This is not isolated to this user:\n   •  368 million Loaded credentials from auth.v2.file log entries in the last 24 hours\n   •  Across 3,942 users and 34,915 sessions\n   •  Top user alone: 96 million credential load events\n\n   Why 100% CPU?\n\n   The credential loading itself (file I/O) isn't CPU-heavy, but the feedback loop creates:\n   •  Continuous JSON serialization/parsing of credentials (Zod schema validation on every load)\n   •  Continuous telemetry event creation, serialization, and batching\n   •  Continuous fetch() calls with header assembly\n   •  The event loop never goes idle because each flush generates events that schedule new flushes\n\n   Suggested Fixes\n\n   1. Immediate fix -- Don't log credential loads at `info` level: Change logInfo('Loaded credentials from auth.v2.file') to a debug-only log or remove it entirely. This breaks the feedback\n      loop since credential loads won't create telemetry events.\n\n   2. Better fix -- Telemetry `flushToWeb` should NOT use `customFetch`: The telemetry client already uses a hardcoded URL (FACTORY_API_BASE_URL/api/telemetry/cli-ingest) and doesn't need auth\n       headers. It should use native fetch directly instead of the Factory customFetch wrapper that adds auth headers. This eliminates the unnecessary credential loading on every flush.\n\n   3. Additional improvement -- Cache credential load results: CredentialsStorage.load() reads from disk on every call. Adding a short TTL cache (e.g., 30 seconds) with file mtime check would\n      eliminate redundant disk I/O for the many callers that hit it in parallel.\n\n   4. Additional improvement -- Rate-limit or deduplicate telemetry events: Consider deduplicating repeated identical log messages to prevent amplification loops.\n\n\nperhaps ONLY log whenever we determ